# MANDATORY: Coworker Delegation Rule for Cursor

## Rule of thumb

Cursor agent = thinking. Coworker = I/O.

## Tools

CLI binary: `~/.local/bin/coworker`. Four subcommands:

- `coworker ask --provider <p> --profile <pr> --paths <f1> <f2> ... --question "<q>"`
- `coworker write --provider <p> --profile <pr> --spec "<what>" --context <ref1> ... --target <out>`
- `coworker stats --since 7d --by profile`
- `coworker rtk {install|enable|disable|status}` (optional plugin — see RTK section)

Profiles: `code` (default, generic analysis), `datarim` (Datarim artifacts), `social` (posts), `write` (boilerplate). Cost-sensitive tasks → `--provider deepseek` (~14x cheaper output vs Moonshot).

## ALWAYS delegate via coworker ask when ANY trigger fires

- Total estimated tokens to read >15000 (sum across files — roughly a single large file the read-guard flags at ~10k est-tokens, or several mid-size files together; the guard estimates tokens as `wc -c / divisor`, so assume large/dense files trip it).
- ≥3 files for one question.
- Any read from `wiki/_raw_/`.
- Bootstrap reads (tasks.md + backlog.md + CLAUDE.md + PRD + plan) — one call, not per-file Read.
- `git diff` / `git log -p` output >~200 lines.

## ALWAYS write through coworker write first, then surgical edit

- First draft of PRD, plan, design docs, task-description.
- Articles in `wiki/`, posts in `Social Media/`, ecosystem-site docs.
- Never accept blindly — after `coworker write`, read output and edit judgment-parts only.

## File-type policy (critical — common friction point)

By default `coworker ask` accepts ONLY `.md`, `.markdown`, `.txt` files. Passing `.py`/`.ts`/`.js`/`.rs`/`.go`/`.sh`/`.mdc` exits 6 with: 'file X (extension .y) is not in the allowed list'. For code reads that trip a trigger (>15000 est-tokens / ≥3 files), opt in with `--allow-code` or `COWORKER_ALLOW_CODE=1`.

For code delegation, explicitly add ONE of:

- `--allow-code` flag, OR
- `COWORKER_ALLOW_CODE=1` environment variable prefix.

Example:

```
coworker ask --allow-code --provider deepseek --profile code --paths src/foo.py src/bar.py --question "..."
```

Do NOT retry after exit 6 — use the flag from the first invocation when reading code files. Prefer the explicit `--allow-code` flag (override stays visible in shell history).

## RTK plugin (opt-in, Rust Token Killer)

RTK is an OPTIONAL coworker plugin for extra token savings via local `rtk` rust binary (https://github.com/Arcanada-one/rtk). Default-OFF; explicit opt-in required.

Commands:

- `coworker rtk install` — prints OS-specific install instructions (macOS / Linux / Windows)
- `coworker rtk enable` — adds idempotent hook to `~/.claude/settings.json` (marker `_managed_by: coworker-rtk`)
- `coworker rtk disable` — removes hook, settings.json back to pre-enable state
- `coworker rtk status` — shows binary path/version + hook on/off

Enable when bulk reads regularly exceed ~5k tokens (logs, code dumps, long diffs). Skip for short tasks.

## NEVER delegate

- Tasks under ~2000 tokens (overhead exceeds savings).
- Debugging, root-cause analysis, race conditions, safety-critical logic.
- Architectural decisions and trade-offs.
- When exact line numbers are needed for Edit (coworker summaries lose them).
- Reasoning about user intent.
- Appending to an existing file via `coworker write --target Y` without `--append`. Bare `coworker write --target Y` truncate-writes Y (Python `'w'` mode) — a spec like `--spec "append section X to file Y" --target Y` overwrites Y with only the new section and destroys everything else (frontmatter, prior sections). Since coworker v0.4.0 the canonical fix is the `--append` flag: `coworker write --append --target Y --spec "..."` (mutually exclusive with `--stdout`, falls back to write if Y does not yet exist, inserts separator newline when needed). Legacy workarounds (`--stdout` + manual concat, or feed Y as `--context` to a fresh `--target`, or native surgical edit) only when byte-exact tail handling matters.

## Failure modes

If provider API key unset / out of balance: scripts fail loudly. Fallback to native Read for that turn only. Switch provider with `--provider <other>`.

